Yes, and that's expected behavior.

These are root GraphQL types, not data models.

type Query struct {
}

type Mutation struct {
}

type Subscription struct {
}

They are essentially marker types that gqlgen uses internally to build the GraphQL schema.

For example, when you implement

func (r *Resolver) Query() QueryResolver {
    return &queryResolver{r}
}

the generated code associates your queryResolver with this generated Query type.

Why are they still generated?

Because you didn't provide your own Go types for them in gqlgen.yml.

You mapped

User
Post
Comment
CreateUserInput
CreatePostInput
CreateCommentInput

but you did not map

Query
Mutation
Subscription

So gqlgen generates them automatically.

Should you create your own?

No.

These structs:

type Query struct{}
type Mutation struct{}
type Subscription struct{}

carry no data.

They're never returned from the database, never mapped, and never contain business logic.

Creating your own versions provides essentially no benefit.

In production

Almost every gqlgen project leaves these generated.

Only the actual GraphQL object types are customized.

So it's perfectly normal to have:

internal/
    manualmodel/
        User
        Post
        Comment
        CreateUserInput
        ...

graph/model/models_gen.go
    Query
    Mutation
    Subscription
My recommendation

I would leave them exactly as they are.

The only types worth owning yourself are the ones that:

need hidden fields (UserID, PostID)
are mapped from entities
are returned by resolvers
are accepted as resolver inputs

Those are:

✅ User
✅ Post
✅ Comment
✅ CreateUserInput
✅ CreatePostInput
✅ CreateCommentInput

Everything else (Query, Mutation, Subscription) can remain generated. That's the approach used in most gqlgen codebases because those types are just placeholders and don't benefit from customization.